observations.recommendation:
We recommended and Management agreed to require:

1) The Officer In-charge of PDAO to submit the required Annual Accomplishment Reports for CY 2022 and onwards, to facilitate evaluation of the proper recording, reporting and utilization of PWD funds;

2) The Sanggunian Panlungsod to create and/or adopt the establishment of the Disability Affairs Officer by duly filling-up the positions of the Disability Affairs Officer following the qualification standards, position titles and salary grades set by RA No. 10070 subject to the qualification requirements as approved by the CSC; 

3) The City HRMO to comply with the requirement of reservation for PWD of at least one percent of all regular and non-regular position in the City Government of Pagadian; and

4) The adherence to AO No. 35 in allocating 1 percent of the City’s Budget for implementation of ensuing PPAs and celebrations.

Recommendations
We recommended and Management agreed to:
Require the City Accounting Office to:
Analyze and investigate further the causes of the noted variances among the FS, GL and  the GSO records, and prepare the necessary adjusting entries;
Update and maintain regularly the subsidiary ledgers (SLs);
Compute the depreciation of all the properties including the Work/Zoo animals account to ensure fair presentation of the assets, depreciation and its related expense accounts in the FS;
Update the lapsing schedule once the data is complete and make necessary adjustments to reflect the correct amount of reported PPEs and related accumulated depreciation for the fair presentation of FS;
Regularly monitor and reconcile the GL and SL of each account;
Require the  City General Services Office (CGSO) to make as much as possible, a detailed analysis of items recorded as PPE, categorize/classify each item in accordance with COA Circular No. 2015-009, and reconcile regularly their records with the Accounting Office to establish the accuracy of the recorded balances of the PPE accounts.
Create an appraisal team with the City Assessor’s Office to assist the Inventory Committee in establishing the value of the land acquired in the previous years in accordance with the Manual on Real Property Appraisal and Assessment Operation and record the value of the Land in the books of accounts;
Create the Disposal Committee to review the residual values and expedite the disposal of unserviceable assets;
Require the Inventory Committee:
To coordinate with GSO and Accounting Office, and observe the regular conduct of the physical count of all properties of the City to update the RPCPPE and facilitate reconciliation of records; and
Expedite the disposal of unserviceable assets;

We recommended and Management agreed to require:

1) The Accounting Office to apply the criteria on capitalization of PPE as prescribed in COA Circular No. 2022-004 to ensure proper classification of assets in the books and make the necessary adjustments to correct and/or restate the balances of affected accounts;

The GSO to: 

2) Provide data to the Accounting Office relevant to items reclassified as semi-expendable property including information of its condition;

3) Update existing PPE and Inventory records and prepare and maintain the additional necessary forms/reports/ registries for purposes of record-keeping and installation of controls over semi-expendable properties provided in Section 4 of the Circular; and

4) Moving forward, use the ICS for issuance of semi-expendable items to establish monitoring, control and accountability over them.

We recommended that Management:

1) Require and monitor the Disbursing Officers concerned, both regular and special, to properly maintain and update their cashbooks in accordance with the pertinent provisions of the NGAS Manual for LGUs, including their respective certification of ending balances, for the proper recording and accounting of their cash transactions to ensure accurate cash balances and the integrity of the cash records;

2) Review and properly implement in the Treasury Office the regular process of monitoring and/or checking the respective cashbooks of the SDOs to ensure correct and updated recording. Consider assigning personnel to focus on this activity since the SDOs are not organic personnel of the Treasury Office;

Require the SDOs concerned to learn how to maintain their cashbook in accordance with existing laws, rules and regulation and/or procedures, as follows:

3) Update the cashbook regularly;

4) Closely monitor cash balance by reconciling daily cash on hand with the cash balance in the cashbook to ensure the accuracy and physical existence of Cash on Hand; 

5)  Reconcile the cashbook balance with the accounting records every end of the month. Make necessary corrections should there be a difference between these two records;

6) Require the Accounting personnel to reclassify and use the proper account codes relative to cash advances as provided under the List of Accounts, Volume III of the NGAS Manual for LGUs; and

7) Require the Accounting personnel to observe faithful recording of all the agency’s financial transactions, especially cash transactions, to safeguard against inaccurate or misleading information.

We recommended and Management agreed to require:

1) The Collecting Officers to faithfully enforce the daily full remittance and turn-over of collections with the RCDs to the Liquidating Officer to preclude the loss or misuse of cash in their possession;

2) The proper bonding of all AO of the City, including the Sub-Collectors, whose duties and responsibilities permit or require the possession or custody of local funds, so that all collectors will maintain and record all their collection in their RCDs;

3) The proper orientation/reorientation of the duties, functions and the corresponding liabilities of a collecting officer and the sub-collectors; and

4) Consider hiring regular Collecting Officers to keep up with the collection process of the City, as the City is gearing up to be a highly urbanized City.

We recommended and Management agreed to:

1) Require the LCU to establish its own internal policies, procedures and guidelines for the recruitment and appointment of faculty members, which shall be submitted to the CSC for approval;

2) Cause the preparation and submission of copies of the required documents and or reports to facilitate evaluation of the operations of the PCIC; and

We recommended that:

1) Management require the submission to the NCPAM the necessary documents and/or justification needed to support procurement of subject drugs and medicines not listed in the PNF, and onwards require:

2) The City Accountant, before effecting payment on the procurement of drugs and medicines demand the submission of certifications/documents as provided for in COA Circular No. 2012-001 and RA No. 9502;

3) The Bids and Awards Committee – Technical Working Group (BAC-TWG) to require the supplier during post-qualification process the submission of Certificate of Product Registration of each drug/medicine being procured to ensure that these are duly registered with the DOH-FDA;

4) The City Health Officer to submit the approved request from the NCPAM of the procured drugs/medicines, proving that the drugs and medicines procured not listed in the PNDF Volume 1 were justified;

5) The creation and/or designation of separate Inspectorate Teams to conduct inspection of deliveries in accordance to specification whether technical or not, or classified as office supplies and materials, drugs and medicines, etc.; and

We recommended and Management agreed to:

1) Maximize the use of the biometric machine by registering all the City employees to the Biometric System whether casual, contractual and job order and the printed copy of the biometric records to be used to support their claims of salaries to ensure the actual time work rendered without prejudice to a Logbook maintained by each office, if any, as an added control procedure;

2) For personnel assigned to field work duty, require the maintenance of attendance logbooks or any other means of recording attendance indicating respective names and signature as well as the time of arrival to and departure from the office to support their manual DTRs;

3) Attach the travel order, memorandum, office order and/or any form of documents that would indicate the exemptions from the use of biometric machines for attendance of personnel on field work;

4) Consider installing additional biometric machines to strategic places or offices such as the City Commercial Center (C3), Agora Public Market, Integrated Bus Terminal (IBT), Motor Pool, Fish Port, Slaughter House and City Engineering Office to accommodate the volume of LGU employees that will be using the biometric machines within their place of assignment, if deemed necessary, considering the distance of their work area from the City Hall grounds;

5) Strictly comply with the form and substance of a contract of employment under existing CSC laws, rules and regulations; and

6) Faithfully comply with the “Daily Wage Basis” or the “No Work, No Pay” Policy, as the case maybe, regardless of the number of days an employee work in a month to ensure just compensation to an employee.

We recommended that the Management:
Maximize the implementation of PPAs under the GAD fund to contribute to the attainment of the advocacy for gender equity and equality;
Require the submission of the following reports, by the concerned personnel in-charge and onwards ensure their regular submission to facilitate evaluation of the proper recording, reporting and utilization of GAD funds:
Annual GAD Plan and Budget – upon approval by the DILG Regional Office Section (Section 4.C.6.7)
Annual GAD Accomplishment Report – after the end of the year (Section 4.C.8.1) accompanied by (Section 4.C.8.5):
Brief summary of the reported program or project;
Copies of the reported policy issuance;
Results of HGDG test; and
Actions taken by the LGU on the COA audit findings and recommendations

We recommended that management require the faithful compliance of the provisions of the COA Circular No. 2015-008 to ensure the proper valuation of the Local Road Network System and its affected accounts in the FS and require that:

4. The Accounting Unit record back to the GF books of accounts the Local Road Network account, maintain its subsidiary ledger and strictly follow the recording and reporting guidelines as provided in the Circular;

Accounts should be traced back to the amount of roads network transferred to the registry and should be recorded considering its depreciation and/or carrying amount (Section VII.a);

